http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: An identified realm of data, representing the circumstances in which the data can be considered true. Examples are (1) intentional contexts such as a requirement definition, a plan or a design, (2) actual contexts such as actual activity execution or a model of constructed building (as-built model), or (3) a time period when a statement holds.

Context framework is an identified collection of contexts that belong together. Examples are (1) a framework of design contexts consisting of as-is, as-designed, and as-built contexts, (2) a framework of management contexts consisting of contexts for planned and actual execution, and (3) a framework for levels of detail such as BIMForum2018 LOD model.

A set of active contexts. It can include a compatible set of contexts for design information (e.g., LOD400 BIM models), organizational structures (e.g., location breakdown structure), a currenty valid master plan, compatible lookahead plan, the week plan for current week, and a context for actual execution data. The can be a unique "current ContexSet" and there can be ContextSet for different periods of time or for different renovation scenarios.
Specifies what units and quantity kinds are used for a specified property in the content graph.
A collection of Specifies what units and quantity kinds are used for a specified property in the content graph
A context that is active in the ContextSet
A context that contains data about intentions or expectations: plans, designs, simulation results, and so on.
Association of a context to the named graph that contains the contents of the context. A context may have multiple content graphs.

Association between two contexts in different context frameworks, indicating that the content of the first context depends on or is based on the content in the second context. For example, a construction plan can be based on a particular LOD model of the design.
A context that contains data about actually happened activities or implemented entities
Relation of a Context to a UnitFramework
Digital Construction Entities Ontology defines the essential entities that can be referred to in construction and renovation projects by people or systems.
Def: A process that is intentionally performed by an agent.
A Context relative to an Activity, representing the situation, for example, at the start, at execution time, or at the end of an activity
Agents are actors or stakeholders associated with construction lifecycles

An object that is needed to perform an activity, and when used is in continuous control of the agent involved in the activity.

Examples: Vehices, cranes, and tools such as hammers and drills
A separately used part of a building
Minimum bounding box of an entity given by a minimum cartesian position and maximum cartesian position
Cartesian position expressed as x, y, and z coordinates with respect to a spatial origin and spatial orientation
Cartesian volume given by the lengths to x, y, and z directions

Category is a labeling of an entity the associates it with some defined class of things. For example, an object can be associated with a particular class in a classification system such as OmniClass, UniFormat, CoClass, or Talo2000. Category allows also to associate an entity with a category of entities represented in an external system or belonging to a particular project.

A function that inheres in one or more pieces of computing hardware. The actualization or manifestation of a computational function is an essentially end-directed activity in virtue kind or kinds of contexts the computing hardware is made for.
An equipment for moving objects. The crane remains stationary during the movement and usually there is a difference in altitude in the origin and target location of the object movement.

An object that performs a function, requiring at most only intermittent control by a user (an agent).

Examples: Sensor, actuator, dishwasher, heater.
Category that contains all entities in a scope of a given entity. For example, all entities in a system, or within a scope of a plan.
Machinery and tools used in construction activities. Equipment do not have a capability to operate activities by itself automatically.
Minimum bounding box of a geodetic area determined by its minimum geodetic position and maximum geodetic position
Geodetic position expressed in longitude, latitude and altitude with respect to a geodetic coordinate system.
A set of entities. Examples are a procurement package, a shipment, a workgroup, or the walls of a space.
Identifier allows the specification of a (global or local) identifier, based on the given identification system (GUID, URI, room number in a building, etc.)
Identifiable information content. Examples are a BIM model, a drawing, a specification, an image, a message, and an issue. Separate from physical information carriers.

Labeling is a generic mechanism to associate entities with any number of labels that are unique within a given category. The purpose is to enable the representation of connections to existing systems, databases or classification schemes.

A (logical) place where material entities can be located or activities can occur. Locations can form a hierarchy, for example, in a location breakdown structure consisting of a site, buildings, floors, zones, spaces, and workspaces
Material batch refers to the collection of homogeneous physical substance that participates in the construction project as the input of a process.
A building unit used for purposes other than living, such as commercial,  service or storage functions.
Orientation in two dimensions given by the orientation angle from true north
A property consisting of land or buildings.

A building unit that is used as a residence.

Examples: apartment, condomium, studio.

A generically dependent continuant that encodes a representation of one or more computational functions (realizable functions)
(Duncan, William. "Making Ontological Sense of Hardware and Software." https://cse.buffalo.edu/~rapaport/584/S10/duncan09-HWSWOnt.pdf (2009))
The dimensions of a spatial region
A position in a space
A quality that concerns the spatial aspects of an entity
Orientation given by three angles: angle about x-axis (alpha), angle about y-axis(beta) and angle about z-axis (gamma)
Orientation of a plane in two dimensions given by its angle about true north (the strike) and the angle of its slope (the dip)
An equipment for transporting shipments. The vehice also moves from origin to the target of the transportation activity. Examples are trucks or forklifts.
A site of work. There can be multiple different kinds of workspaces needed by an activity: labor crew space, equipment space, hazard space, and so on.
The context in which the content of the information content entity is represented
Defines the broader category that is the scope of the label
The information content entity that is the source of the data represented in this context
Artihmetic constraints have an operator (hasOperator) and are of the form: variable1 operator variable2 = variable3. For example, startTime + duration = endTime.
A Constraint between two Variables
Comparison operator between variables. Examples: equal or less than.
Combination of other constraints, either elementary or composite ones. Examples are conjunctive composition (and) or negated composition (not).
Constraint that is a conjuction (logical and) of the constituent constraints

A constraint limits the possible values that specified variables can simultaneously have. Examples are that values of a set of variables need to be same, or all different, or that the value of first variable is less than the value of second one.
A constraint that states that the involved variables have different values
Constraint that is a disjuction (logical ord) of the constituent constraints
Constraint that limits the distance between variable1 and variable2.
Constraint that does not have other more simple constraints as its parts.
A domain of enumerated values. Should be used with object properties
Constraint that specifies that the distance of variable1 and variable2 is a fixed value.
Ordered domain that is represented with the minimum and maximum limits. Useful for example in temporal reasoning.
A BinaryConstraint for the value of variable1 to be less than the value of variable2
Constraint representing that variable1 is less than variable2
Constraint that limits the distance of variable1 and variable2 to be less than or equal to fixed maximum value.
A UnaryConstraint that limits the maximum value of the variable
Constraint that limits the distance of variable1 and variable2 to be greater than or equal to fixed minimum value.
A UnaryConstraint that limits the minimum value of the variable
A composite constraint that is negation of its constituent constraints (conjunctively, if there are multiple)
A unary constraint that limits the values of a variable to one of the enumerated values
Artihmetic operators, such as plus, minus, times and divide.
A domain of ordered values. Should be used with DataProperties that have ordered domains (such as numbers).
An objectified property
Constraint that limits the value of the variable to be a fixed value.
A constraint for all involved variables to have same values
Constraint between three variables.
A Constraint on one Variable
A representation of a property that can assume different values, possibly limited by constraints
An instance/literal level representation for the set of possible values that can be given to the variable
A Constraint that is applicable in a Context
The Comparison operator of an ArithmeticConstraint. For example, in 'variable1 LessThan variable2' the Comparison operator is LessThan
A Constraint that is part of a CompositeConstraint
Associates an objectified property to any entity
A relation to associate a Variable to any object
A relation to associate a Constraint with a Variable
The first variable of a constraint
The second variable of a constraint
The third variable of a constraint
The relation that associates a Variable with a VariableDomain
The Context in which the Constraint is applicable
The relation that associates a Property with a Constraint
Associates the Property to the thing whose property it is
The relation that associates a VariableDomain with a Variable
The property that associates a Variable with the property whose variable it is
The relation that associates the Variable with the object to which the variable belongs to
